{{Infobox book |italic title = <!--(see above)--> |name = Algebraic Geometry |image = file:Robin Hartshorne2.jpg |image_size = |caption = [[Robin Hartshorne]] is the author of ''Algebraic Geometry''. |alt = Robin Hartshorne |author = |audio_read_by = |title_orig = |orig_lang_code = |title_working = |translator = |illustrator = |cover_artist = |country = |language = English |series = |subject = Algebraic geometry |genre = Textbook |set_in = |published = 1977 |media_type = |pages = |awards = |isbn = |oclc = |dewey = |congress = |preceded_by = |followed_by = |wikisource = |exclude_cover = }} '''''Algebraic Geometry''''' is an influential,<ref>[[MathSciNet]] lists more than 2500 citations of this book.</ref> [[algebraic geometry]] [[textbook]] written by [[Robin Hartshorne]] and published by [[Springer-Verlag]] in 1977.
==Importance== It was the first extended treatment of [[scheme theory]] written as a text intended to be accessible to graduate students.
==Contents== The first chapter, titled "Varieties", deals with the classical algebraic geometry of [[algebraic variety|varieties]] over algebraically closed fields. This chapter uses many classical results in [[commutative algebra]], including [[Hilbert's Nullstellensatz]], with the books by Atiyah&ndash;Macdonald, Matsumura, and Zariski&ndash;Samuel as usual references. The second and the third chapters, "Schemes" and "Cohomology", form the technical heart of the book. The last two chapters, "Curves" and "Surfaces", respectively explore the geometry of 1-dimensional and 2-dimensional objects, using the tools developed in the Chapters 2 and 3.
